2538,-0.03899453,0.00003469,-0.00129886,-0.05036657,0.00603737,0.02742440,-0.00210177,-0.03388963,-0.03925120,0.11894284,0.01600008,0.07471734,0.01497599,0.00638146,0.00097030,0.00695070,-0.00739382,-0.04421938,0.02649857,-0.04770144,0.05611860,0.05818495,-0.01193478,-0.03698142,0.01717700,-0.01309042,0.01343745,-0.01645152,-0.06338801,-0.00612352,0.04807132,0.05891997,-0.00710690,-0.06006698,-0.00352473,-0.07264854,0.04720564,-0.02007264,0.03679912,0.10374933,-0.00001203,-0.02781457]',E'View Routes\n\nIf your route only needs to return a [view](/docs/{{version}}/views), you may use the `Route::view` method. Like the `redirect` method, this method provides a simple shortcut so that you do not have to define a full route or controller. The `view` method accepts a URI as its first argument and a view name as its second argument. In addition, you may provide an array of data to pass to the view as an optional third argument:\n\n```php\nRoute::view(''/welcome'', ''welcome'');\n\nRoute::view(''/welcome'', ''welcome'', [''name'' => ''Taylor'']);\n```\n\n> [!WARNING]\n> When using route parameters in view routes, the following parameters are reserved by Laravel and cannot be used: `view`, `data`, `status`, and `headers`.\n\n<a name="listing-your-routes"></a>','{"source": "laravel", "version": "12", "language": "php", "title": "Routing", "section_title": "routing", "url": "https://github.com/laravel/docs/blob/12.x/routing.md", "topics": "laravel,php,routing", "categories": "web,php,fullstack,orm"}');
