45709,-0.05958484,0.00873137,-0.00243189,0.01092752,0.04014890,0.07197986,0.00173975,-0.01999035,-0.05292454,0.08998469,-0.00539269,0.07160545,-0.02083150,-0.02849359,-0.01117346,0.00912140,-0.00506073,-0.08737744,0.00555311,-0.01429655,-0.03816936,0.03908786,-0.03268594,-0.00862352,-0.05157659,-0.01944100,0.05723116,0.04528714,-0.04863268,-0.01816861,0.00228009,0.05815594,0.00226857,0.03305974,-0.00468698,-0.03648708,0.07698748,-0.07345542,0.03050461,0.08626492,0.00758623,-0.01775995]',E'Required Parameters\n\nSometimes you will need to capture segments of the URI within your route. For example, you may need to capture a user''s ID from the URL. You may do so by defining route parameters:\n\n```php\nRoute::get(''/user/{id}'', function (string $id) {\n    return ''User ''.$id;\n});\n```\n\nYou may define as many route parameters as required by your route:\n\n```php\nRoute::get(''/posts/{post}/comments/{comment}'', function (string $postId, string $commentId) {\n    // ...\n});\n```\n\nRoute parameters are always encased within `{}` braces and should consist of alphabetic characters. Underscores (`_`) are also acceptable within route parameter names. Route parameters are injected into route callbacks / controllers based on their order - the names of the route callback / controller arguments do not matter.\n\n<a name="parameters-and-dependency-injection"></a>','{"source": "laravel", "version": "12", "language": "php", "title": "Routing", "section_title": "routing", "url": "https://github.com/laravel/docs/blob/12.x/routing.md", "topics": "laravel,php,routing", "categories": "web,php,fullstack,orm"}');
