277514,-0.04695900,0.01723634,-0.02277626,0.07011150,0.00454600,-0.01370272,-0.05295747,-0.06503989,0.06725518,0.00355277,0.00043086,-0.03001220,0.01919785,-0.01385946,-0.03216889,-0.00331379,-0.06004511,0.05060339,0.03033321,0.02438382,0.00183482,-0.05475553,-0.06384046,-0.05452315,-0.01510767,0.06626171,0.02863858,-0.10939845,-0.01276039,-0.01003304,0.06158249,0.00509379,-0.01456608,-0.02945636,-0.02847365,0.01481734,0.04677381,-0.00668493,0.03341303,-0.05296221,-0.02945020]',E'Throttling With Redis\n\nBy default, the `throttle` middleware is mapped to the `Illuminate\\Routing\\Middleware\\ThrottleRequests` class. However, if you are using Redis as your application''s cache driver, you may wish to instruct Laravel to use Redis to manage rate limiting. To do so, you should use the `throttleWithRedis` method in your application''s `bootstrap/app.php` file. This method maps the `throttle` middleware to the `Illuminate\\Routing\\Middleware\\ThrottleRequestsWithRedis` middleware class:\n\n```php\n->withMiddleware(function (Middleware $middleware): void {\n    $middleware->throttleWithRedis();\n    // ...\n})\n```\n\n<a name="form-method-spoofing"></a>','{"source": "laravel", "version": "12", "language": "php", "title": "Routing", "section_title": "routing", "url": "https://github.com/laravel/docs/blob/12.x/routing.md", "topics": "laravel,php,routing", "categories": "web,php,fullstack,orm"}');
