.15389833,-0.00315156,-0.02026297,0.03359310,0.02252274,-0.04889579,0.05524363,0.02421222,-0.01206211,0.00801693,0.08370974,-0.01432311,0.00933761,-0.04636035,-0.03822078,0.00620260,0.02107425,0.00062269,-0.05738251,0.04164261,-0.02679569,-0.03367539,0.01589477,-0.00067055,-0.04884917,0.03782231,-0.00600285,0.02667594,0.03477170,-0.05941231,-0.02215460,-0.01280657,0.07752547,0.04504979,-0.03075191,0.04261283,-0.01414536,0.05099094,0.05280834,0.07098902,-0.00143886,0.00919054,-0.05676587]',E'Soft Deleted Models\n\nTypically, implicit model binding will not retrieve models that have been [soft deleted](/docs/{{version}}/eloquent#soft-deleting), and will instead return a 404 HTTP response. However, you can instruct the framework to allow soft deleted models by invoking the `withTrashed` method when defining your resource route:\n\n```php\nuse App\\Http\\Controllers\\PhotoController;\n\nRoute::resource(''photos'', PhotoController::class)->withTrashed();\n```\n\nCalling `withTrashed` with no arguments will allow soft deleted models for the `show`, `edit`, and `update` resource routes. You may specify a subset of these routes by passing an array to the `withTrashed` method:\n\n```php\nRoute::resource(''photos'', PhotoController::class)->withTrashed([''show'']);\n```\n\n<a name="specifying-the-resource-model"></a>','{"source": "laravel", "version": "12", "language": "php", "title": "Controllers", "section_title": "controllers", "url": "https://github.com/laravel/docs/blob/12.x/controllers.md", "topics": "laravel,php,controllers", "categories": "web,php,fullstack,orm"}');
