00759844,-0.04131179,0.01899088,0.05747826,0.03511465,0.02661244,0.05902807,-0.05959393,0.00066423,0.14607827,-0.02341890,-0.00001314,-0.05763320,-0.00366109,-0.04516646,-0.01142593,-0.07808714,-0.11601879,0.01647560,0.00512771,0.02716730,0.01261983,0.01321038,-0.04268213,-0.02711244,-0.07028399,-0.00545979,-0.02377552,-0.03620164,0.03319762,-0.02436814,-0.01666127,0.00521512,-0.06168881,0.03504939,0.01261362,0.06482337,0.00813980,-0.00148180,0.04280718,0.00873272,-0.02573332]',E'Replicating Models\n\nYou may create an unsaved copy of an existing model instance using the `replicate` method. This method is particularly useful when you have model instances that share many of the same attributes:\n\n```php\nuse App\\Models\\Address;\n\n$shipping = Address::create([\n    ''type'' => ''shipping'',\n    ''line_1'' => ''123 Example Street'',\n    ''city'' => ''Victorville'',\n    ''state'' => ''CA'',\n    ''postcode'' => ''90001'',\n]);\n\n$billing = $shipping->replicate()->fill([\n    ''type'' => ''billing''\n]);\n\n$billing->save();\n```\n\nTo exclude one or more attributes from being replicated to the new model, you may pass an array to the `replicate` method:\n\n```php\n$flight = Flight::create([\n    ''destination'' => ''LAX'',\n    ''origin'' => ''LHR'',\n    ''last_flown'' => ''2020-03-04 11:00:00'',\n    ''last_pilot_id'' => 747,\n]);\n\n$flight = $flight->replicate([\n    ''last_flown'',\n    ''last_pilot_id''\n]);\n```\n\n<a name="query-scopes"></a>','{"source": "laravel", "version": "12", "language": "php", "title": "Eloquent: Getting Started", "section_title": "eloquent", "url": "https://github.com/laravel/docs/blob/12.x/eloquent.md", "topics": "laravel,php,eloquent", "categories": "web,php,fullstack,orm"}');
